<DocsLayout title="Configuration" description="Configure lean-ctx for your editor and project.">
  <p>
    lean-ctx works out of the box with zero configuration. The Rust binary handles MCP server mode,
    shell hook mode, and all compression patterns automatically.
  </p>

  <h2>MCP Server Configuration</h2>
  <p>
    Configure your editor to use lean-ctx as an MCP server. See the
    <a href="/docs/installation">Installation guide</a> for editor-specific instructions.
  </p>

  <h2>Shell Hook Configuration</h2>
  <p>The fastest way is automatic setup:</p>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx init --global</code></pre>
  <p>Or add aliases manually to your <code>.zshrc</code> or <code>.bashrc</code>:</p>
  <pre><code>alias git='lean-ctx -c git'
alias npm='lean-ctx -c npm'
alias cargo='lean-ctx -c cargo'
alias docker='lean-ctx -c docker'
alias grep='lean-ctx -c grep'
alias find='lean-ctx -c find'
alias ls='lean-ctx -c ls'
alias curl='lean-ctx -c curl'</code></pre>

  <p>Or use lean-ctx as a Cursor terminal profile:</p>
  <pre><code>{`{
  "terminal.integrated.profiles.osx": {
    "lean-ctx": {
      "path": "/path/to/lean-ctx",
      "args": ["shell"],
      "icon": "terminal"
    }
  }
}`}</code></pre>

  <h2>Cursor Rule</h2>
  <p>
    For maximum token savings, add a <code>.cursor/rules/lean-ctx.mdc</code> to your project.
    This instructs the LLM to prefer lean-ctx tools and use compact output patterns.
    An example is included in <code>examples/lean-ctx.mdc</code> in the repository.
  </p>
  <p>
    The Cursor rule includes CRP v2 (Compact Response Protocol) which reduces
    both output tokens (50-80%) and thinking tokens (30-60%) through structured
    task parsing and one-hypothesis reasoning.
  </p>

  <h2>Command-Line Reference</h2>
  <p>For the full CLI reference, see the <a href="/docs/cli">CLI documentation</a>.</p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Command</th><th>Description</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>lean-ctx</code></td><td>Start MCP server (default, used by editors)</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>lean-ctx init --global</code></td><td>Install shell aliases globally</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>lean-ctx gain</code></td><td>Show persistent token savings dashboard</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>lean-ctx -c &lt;command&gt;</code></td><td>Execute command with compressed output</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>lean-ctx shell</code></td><td>Interactive shell with compression</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>lean-ctx read &lt;file&gt; [-m mode]</code></td><td>Read file with compression (modes: full, map, signatures, aggressive, entropy)</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>lean-ctx diff &lt;file1&gt; &lt;file2&gt;</code></td><td>Compressed file diff</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>lean-ctx grep &lt;pattern&gt; [path]</code></td><td>Compressed search</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>lean-ctx find &lt;pattern&gt; [path]</code></td><td>Compact file finder</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>lean-ctx ls [path]</code></td><td>Token-optimized directory listing</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>lean-ctx deps [path]</code></td><td>Project dependencies summary</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>lean-ctx --version</code></td><td>Print version</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>lean-ctx --help</code></td><td>Print usage information</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
</DocsLayout>
